{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658653"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:53:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:53:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20809"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20809","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20809"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13684"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96153"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13684","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13684"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20809"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78881"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11578"},{"type":"tags","id":"11742"},{"type":"tags","id":"12642"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32956"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32957"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96153","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96153"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ECells require various mechanisms to acquire nutrients from their environment. The plasma membrane serves as a selective barrier that regulates which substances can enter or leave the cell.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes how glucose typically enters most mammalian cells?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Simple diffusion through the lipid bilayer","Facilitated diffusion via GLUT transporters","Active transport using ATP hydrolysis","Endocytosis via clathrin-coated vesicles","Sodium-dependent secondary active transport"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Efacilitated diffusion via GLUT transporters\u003C/strong\u003E. Most cells acquire glucose through facilitated diffusion, which is mediated by glucose transporter (GLUT) proteins embedded in the plasma membrane. This process allows glucose to move down its concentration gradient without direct energy expenditure, but at a rate much faster than would be possible by simple diffusion alone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESimple diffusion through the lipid bilayer\u003C/strong\u003E - Glucose is a polar molecule that cannot readily cross the hydrophobic core of the plasma membrane by simple diffusion. It requires specific transport proteins.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActive transport using ATP hydrolysis\u003C/strong\u003E - While some nutrients are transported via primary active transport, glucose uptake in most cells does not directly require ATP hydrolysis. However, maintaining the glucose concentration gradient may indirectly require energy.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndocytosis via clathrin-coated vesicles\u003C/strong\u003E - While some nutrients and macromolecules enter cells through endocytosis, glucose typically enters through membrane transporters, not through vesicular uptake.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESodium-dependent secondary active transport\u003C/strong\u003E - This mechanism (via SGLT transporters) is important for glucose absorption in the intestine and reabsorption in the kidney, but most other cells in the body use facilitated diffusion via GLUT transporters.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDifferent GLUT isoforms exist with varying tissue distributions and affinities for glucose. For example, GLUT4 is insulin-responsive and particularly important in muscle and adipose tissue, while GLUT1 is widely expressed in many cell types and provides basal glucose uptake.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Facilitated diffusion allows transport of glucose and other nutrients down their concentration gradient without energy expenditure.","Active transport mechanisms use ATP to move nutrients against their concentration gradient.","Sodium-glucose cotransporters couple the movement of glucose against its concentration gradient with the movement of sodium down its electrochemical gradient."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 1, The Cell as a Unit of Health and Disease; p. 8-11"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78881"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20809"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78881","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78881"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-31T13:16:16+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-31T13:18:05+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13684"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96153"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11578","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11578"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"The cell as a unit of health and disease","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":0,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T15:05:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T15:05:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18